31    /**
32    * DateTime is the standard implementation of an unmodifiable datetime class.
33    * <p>
34    * <code>DateTime</code> is the most widely used implementation of
35    * {@link ReadableInstant}. As with all instants, it represents an exact
36    * point on the time-line, but limited to the precision of milliseconds.
37    * A <code>DateTime</code> calculates its fields with respect to a
38    * {@link DateTimeZone time zone}.
39    * <p>
40    * Internally, the class holds two pieces of data. Firstly, it holds the
41    * datetime as milliseconds from the Java epoch of 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z.
42    * Secondly, it holds a {@link Chronology} which determines how the
43    * millisecond instant value is converted into the date time fields.
44    * The default Chronology is {@link ISOChronology} which is the agreed
45    * international standard and compatible with the modern Gregorian calendar.
46    * <p>
47    * Each individual field can be queried in two ways:
48    * <ul>
49    * <li><code>getHourOfDay()</code>
50    * <li><code>hourOfDay().get()</code>
51    * </ul>
52    * The second technique also provides access to other useful methods on the
53    * field:
54    * <ul>
55    * <li>numeric value
56    * <li>text value
57    * <li>short text value
58    * <li>maximum/minimum values
59    * <li>add/subtract
60    * <li>set
61    * <li>rounding
62    * </ul>
63    * <p>
64    * DateTime is thread-safe and immutable, provided that the Chronology is as well.
65    * All standard Chronology classes supplied are thread-safe and immutable.
66    *
67    * @author Stephen Colebourne
68    * @author Kandarp Shah
69    * @author Brian S O'Neill
70    * @since 1.0
71    * @see MutableDateTime
72    */
 
99.5% Uncovered Elements: 2 (375) Complexity: 143 Complexity Density: 0.71

123    /**
124    * Parses a {@code DateTime} from the specified string.
125    * <p>
126    * This uses {@link ISODateTimeFormat#dateTimeParser()}{@code .withOffsetParsed()}
127    * which is different to passing a {@code String} to the constructor.
128    * <p>
129    * Sometimes this method and {@code new DateTime(str)} return different results.
130    * This can be confusing as the difference is not visible in {@link #toString()}.
131    * <p>
132    * When passed a date-time string without an offset, such as '2010-06-30T01:20',
133    * both the constructor and this method use the default time-zone.
134    * As such, {@code DateTime.parse("2010-06-30T01:20")} and
135    * {@code new DateTime("2010-06-30T01:20"))} are equal.
136    * <p>
137    * However, when this method is passed a date-time string with an offset,
138    * the offset is directly parsed and stored.
139    * As such, {@code DateTime.parse("2010-06-30T01:20+02:00")} and
140    * {@code new DateTime("2010-06-30T01:20+02:00"))} are NOT equal.
141    * The object produced via this method has a zone of {@code DateTimeZone.forOffsetHours(2)}.
142    * The object produced via the constructor has a zone of {@code DateTimeZone.getDefault()}.
143    *
144    * @param str the string to parse, not null
145    * @since 2.0
146    */
 
100% Uncovered Elements: 0 (1) Complexity: 1 Complexity Density: 1

149  9 return parse(str, ISODateTimeFormat.dateTimeParser().withOffsetParsed());

1262    /**
1263    * Returns a copy of this datetime with the specified period taken away.
1264    * <p>
1265    * This method will subtract each element of the period one by one, from
1266    * largest to smallest, adjusting the datetime to be accurate between each.
1267    * <p>
1268    * Thus, subtracting a period of one month and one day from 2007-05-31 will
1269    * work as follows:
1270    * First subtract one month and adjust, resulting in 2007-04-30
1271    * Then subtract one day and adjust, resulting in 2007-04-29.
1272    * Note that the day has been adjusted by two.
1273    * <p>
1274    * This method is typically used to subtract complex period instances.
1275    * Subtracting one field is best achieved using methods
1276    * like {@link #minusYears(int)}.
1277    * <p>
1278    * If the amount is zero or null, then <code>this</code> is returned.

1280    *
1281    * @param period the period to reduce this instant by

2049    /**
2050    * DateTime.Property binds a DateTime to a DateTimeField allowing powerful
2051    * datetime functionality to be easily accessed.
2052    * <p>
2053    * The simplest use of this class is as an alternative get method, here used to
2054    * get the year '1972' (as an int) and the month 'December' (as a String).
2055    * <pre>
2056    * DateTime dt = new DateTime(1972, 12, 3, 0, 0, 0, 0);
2057    * int year = dt.year().get();
2058    * String monthStr = dt.month().getAsText();
2059    * </pre>
2060    * <p>
2061    * Methods are also provided that allow date modification. These return new instances
2062    * of DateTime - they do not modify the original. The example below yields two
2063    * independent immutable date objects 20 years apart.
2064    * <pre>
2065    * DateTime dt = new DateTime(1972, 12, 3, 0, 0, 0, 0);
2066    * DateTime dt20 = dt.year().addToCopy(20);
2067    * </pre>
2068    * Serious modification of dates (ie. more than just changing one or two fields)
2069    * should use the {@link org.joda.time.MutableDateTime MutableDateTime} class.
2070    * <p>
2071    * DateTime.Propery itself is thread-safe and immutable, as well as the
2072    * DateTime being operated on.
2073    *
2074    * @author Stephen Colebourne
2075    * @author Brian S O'Neill
2076    * @since 1.0
2077    */
